<bioghist encodinganalog="545">
<p>Franklin H. Bailey was a soldier from Adrian, Michigan who served in Co. C, 4th Michigan Cavalry during the Civil War. He later was an astronomer, lecturer, and teacher at Hillsdale College. He then moved to Boston, Massachusetts where he invented what was a forerunner of the planetarium.</p>
</bioghist>



<scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
<p>The Franklin H. Bailey collection consists of Civil War letters written to his parents in Adrian, Michigan concerning family affairs and army life. There are also letters he wrote to his wife Minerva while on a trip abroad in 1873. Other materials include a scrapbook of letters, 1880-1901, primarily concerning educational matters; enlistment and discharge certificates; diaries, 1865-1883, detailing his war service, student life at Hillsdale College, and his teaching and scientific interests. There is one Civil War letter, undated, of Minerva Bailey's first husband, Levi Greenfield, who served in Co. C, 18th Michigan Infantry.</p>
</scopecontent>

